  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) was not sent to space all at once, but was assembled in stages over several years:\n\n1. First Component:\n- Zarya module launched on November 20, 1998\n- Launched by Russia using a Proton rocket\n- First functional component of the ISS\n\n2. Initial Assembly:\n- Unity module (U.S. module) launched shortly after on December 4, 1998\n- Connected to Zarya during the first space shuttle mission (STS-88)\n\n3. Continued Construction:\n- Additional modules were launched and assembled between 1998 and 2011\n- Space shuttle missions were crucial in transporting and connecting modules\n- Modules came from multiple countries: Russia, United States, Europe, Japan\n\n4. Completion:\n- Major construction was completed in 2011 when the U.S. Space Shuttle program ended\n- Continuous human presence on the station began on November 2, 2000\n\n5. Current Status:\n- Remains operational and continuously inhabited\n- Collaborative project involving space agencies from multiple countries\n- Serves as a research laboratory and international cooperation platform\n\nThe ISS was a gradual, multinational construction project rather than a single launch event.",
